WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Support us and become VIP member 
to remove all ads from www.OpenSubtitles.org

2
00:00:21.271 --> 00:00:24.900
<i>J.J. ABRAMS: Star Wars is a gift
everywhere you look at it.</i>

3
00:00:25.025 --> 00:00:28.403
one of those gifts is
the ability to work with ILM.

4
00:00:30.280 --> 00:00:32.449
<i>Every time they do a project.
they solve a new problem.</i>

5
00:00:35.118 --> 00:00:38.539
Part of the DNA needs to be
that audacity to think

6
00:00:38.622 --> 00:00:39.790
that we'll figure it out.

7
00:00:41.124 --> 00:00:43.168
<i>that same spirit of fearlessness.</i>

8
00:00:43.252 --> 00:00:46.296
<i>that thread goes throughout ILM
and its history.</i>

9
00:00:48.131 --> 00:00:49.591
ROGER GUYETT: It's not a <i>singular mission.</i>

10
00:00:49.675 --> 00:00:51.718
<i>It's like an army collaborating</i>

11
00:00:51.802 --> 00:00:55.931
to try and create this idea
that everything happened.

12
00:00:56.181 --> 00:00:59.518
<i>If you can somehow create that illusion.</i>

13
00:00:59.601 --> 00:01:01.186
then in my mind. we've succeeded.

14
00:01:03.230 --> 00:01:05.899
We're able to take
the best tools for the craft

15
00:01:05.983 --> 00:01:07.985
<i>and combine different techniques.</i>

16
00:01:08.068 --> 00:01:11.280
<i>They're all there for a reason.
they're all part of the story.</i>

17
00:01:11.363 --> 00:01:12.698
<i>and that comes from Kathy.</i>

18
00:01:12.781 --> 00:01:16.034
<i>She believes.
she is completely fearless.</i>

19
00:01:16.118 --> 00:01:17.661
and that is inspiring.

20
00:01:19.955 --> 00:01:22.332
I love the creative process.

21
00:01:22.416 --> 00:01:26.211
<i>so working with ILM
has been a huge benefit.</i>

22
00:01:26.295 --> 00:01:30.716
<i>and I think the level of imagination
that could be brought into storytelling</i>

23
00:01:30.799 --> 00:01:32.467
<i>expanded exponentially.</i>

24
00:01:34.219 --> 00:01:37.264
We have a really great
art department here.

25
00:01:37.347 --> 00:01:39.933
<i>who worked with J.J.
right from the beginning.</i>

26
00:01:40.017 --> 00:01:43.103
<i>helping spark off story ideas</i>

27
00:01:43.186 --> 00:01:46.565
<i>and delve deeper into the characters.
and I think that comes out in the work.</i>

28
00:01:49.776 --> 00:01:54.239
A lot of the practical skills
that is used in principal photography.

29
00:01:54.323 --> 00:01:56.116
<i>we have folks who have those skills</i>

30
00:01:56.199 --> 00:01:59.953
<i>and we have translated those skills
into the digital realm.</i>

31
00:02:00.037 --> 00:02:02.456
My mind went to.
"How are we going to do this

32
00:02:02.539 --> 00:02:06.710
"in the most convincing possible way
to create this grand illusion?"

33
00:02:08.629 --> 00:02:09.671
J.J. was very specific.

34
00:02:09.755 --> 00:02:11.590
he wanted to build real sets

35
00:02:11.673 --> 00:02:13.925
at the same time as CG
when he needs to.

36
00:02:14.009 --> 00:02:15.802
<i>That was hugely exciting.</i>

37
00:02:18.138 --> 00:02:20.390
The worlds are colliding
in the filmmaking process.

38
00:02:20.474 --> 00:02:24.436
<i>We wanted to use the VFX
purely to fill in the storytelling gaps</i>

39
00:02:24.519 --> 00:02:25.979
<i>so restraint was the huge word</i>

40
00:02:26.063 --> 00:02:28.315
<i>that we used a lot
in the design process.</i>

41
00:02:28.398 --> 00:02:29.399
(CHEWIE CRIES)

42
00:02:29.483 --> 00:02:33.070
There are definitely many
visual challenges in The <i>Force</i> Awakens

43
00:02:33.153 --> 00:02:34.363
<i>that have pushed the bar.</i>

44
00:02:34.446 --> 00:02:38.367
Now that we have offices in Vancouver.
Singapore. London.

45
00:02:38.450 --> 00:02:40.118
<i>as well as in San Francisco.</i>

46
00:02:40.202 --> 00:02:43.664
<i>it's enabled us to bring in
the best artists</i>

47
00:02:43.747 --> 00:02:46.166
<i>in visual effects from around the world.</i>

48
00:02:48.919 --> 00:02:51.088
Han Solo!

49
00:02:51.171 --> 00:02:54.007
Lupita could actually perform
as a normal human

50
00:02:54.091 --> 00:02:57.386
<i>which suddenly released her.
and we could actually composite that</i>

51
00:02:57.469 --> 00:03:00.806
<i>as she was performing on the
motion capture stage in real time.</i>

52
00:03:00.889 --> 00:03:02.891
Somebody said to me.
"What's the magic?"

53
00:03:03.266 --> 00:03:06.186
<i>And to me. the magic is
when we were doing Maz.</i>

54
00:03:06.269 --> 00:03:10.148
<i>You saw Lupita just make
that character come to life.</i>

55
00:03:10.524 --> 00:03:12.901
<i>ABRAMS: She looks like she fits in.</i>

56
00:03:13.276 --> 00:03:16.488
They've done an extraordinary job
bringing a character to life in CG

57
00:03:16.571 --> 00:03:17.948
that you would never know.

58
00:03:20.450 --> 00:03:22.285
There has been an awakening.

59
00:03:22.452 --> 00:03:23.912
Have you felt it?

60
00:03:25.539 --> 00:03:26.832
ANDY SERKIS:
<i>I've thrown in the performance without</i>

61
00:03:26.915 --> 00:03:28.333
<i>knowing how he's going to manifest.</i>

62
00:03:28.417 --> 00:03:29.960
and that's quite exciting. really.

63
00:03:30.127 --> 00:03:32.254
MATT RANK: <i>Andy's a veteran
of performance capture.</i>

64
00:03:32.337 --> 00:03:35.048
and J.J. was very happy
running with him

65
00:03:35.132 --> 00:03:37.217
seeing what ideas he had.
what we could do.

66
00:03:37.300 --> 00:03:40.929
<i>It was quite traditional.
active mo-cap suit. cameras. head cam.</i>

67
00:03:41.012 --> 00:03:44.725
<i>We performed it live on set.
It all went really. really well.</i>

68
00:03:44.808 --> 00:03:49.688
We try incredibly hard to make sure
the audience doesn't suddenly jump

69
00:03:49.771 --> 00:03:51.523
<i>when they see these characters.</i>

70
00:03:51.606 --> 00:03:53.775
PATRICK TUBACH: <i>Maz and Snoke
were both examples of</i>

71
00:03:53.859 --> 00:03:55.986
how can we use technology
that we have today

72
00:03:56.069 --> 00:03:58.196
<i>to bring new characters to life.</i>

73
00:03:58.280 --> 00:04:00.532
<i>Using the performance capture
technology</i>

74
00:04:00.615 --> 00:04:03.034
<i>to have real people inhabit
these characters. I think.</i>

75
00:04:03.118 --> 00:04:06.246
<i>is really just an extension of having
a puppeteer using a puppet.</i>

76
00:04:06.329 --> 00:04:10.083
<i>That's one way that we've been
able to take technology from today</i>

77
00:04:10.167 --> 00:04:12.836
<i>and really breathe new life
into some of these characters.</i>

78
00:04:14.629 --> 00:04:16.047
(RATHTARS ROARING)

79
00:04:18.383 --> 00:04:20.385
HAN: <i>I got</i> a <i>bad feeling about this.</i>

80
00:04:21.178 --> 00:04:25.056
GUYETT: <i>The fun of the rathtars is
we wanted to create this slightly crazy</i>

81
00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:28.310
but just fun moment inside the freighter.

82
00:04:29.853 --> 00:04:32.105
Those kind of creatures.
you couldn't really do practically.

83
00:04:32.189 --> 00:04:35.317
<i>We had these huge creatures
with these huge mouths</i>

84
00:04:35.400 --> 00:04:37.277
<i>and super long tentacles
grabbing people.</i>

85
00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:39.571
<i>That kind of stuff is great
when you do it in CG.</i>

86
00:04:39.738 --> 00:04:42.783
It was sort of like a mini.
"Release the kraken."

87
00:04:42.866 --> 00:04:45.285
<i>with these crazy creatures
moving around.</i>

88
00:04:45.368 --> 00:04:49.080
<i>They did this really wild thing
where the creature would roll</i>

89
00:04:49.164 --> 00:04:51.875
<i>and it just gave it a completely
different kind of quality.</i>

90
00:04:54.127 --> 00:04:59.090
It was a weird rathtar.
<i>Indiana</i> Jones homage <i>in</i> there.

91
00:05:00.217 --> 00:05:02.217
DAVE FOGLER:
<i>We know what a TIE fighter looks like.</i>

92
00:05:02.844 --> 00:05:04.888
<i>We know what an X-wing looks like.</i>

93
00:05:04.971 --> 00:05:07.057
This movie has new versions.

94
00:05:07.557 --> 00:05:09.309
OSCAR ISAAC: <i>A black X-wing.</i>

95
00:05:09.392 --> 00:05:11.152
The coolest thing
I've ever heard in my life.

96
00:05:17.275 --> 00:05:20.153
As a kid. I knew how to draw an X-wing
and a TIE fighter

97
00:05:20.237 --> 00:05:23.114
<i>simply because it took like four lines
to draw those things.</i>

98
00:05:24.574 --> 00:05:25.867
PAUL KAVANAGH:
<i>My seventh birthday.</i>

99
00:05:25.951 --> 00:05:27.202
<i>I come out of the theater</i>

100
00:05:27.285 --> 00:05:29.871
<i>and I want to make those spaceships
fly on the screen.</i>

101
00:05:29.955 --> 00:05:33.208
<i>Cut to 38 years later.
and I'm sitting here.</i>

102
00:05:33.291 --> 00:05:35.919
and my mom calls me up and says.

103
00:05:36.002 --> 00:05:39.047
"Son. you're doing it.
you're the guy flying the spaceships."

104
00:05:41.508 --> 00:05:43.635
The <i>Falcon</i> is a real character
in the movie.

105
00:05:43.718 --> 00:05:45.053
and people know it very well.

106
00:05:45.136 --> 00:05:48.640
<i>Flying the</i> Falcon <i>through the graveyard
and then getting chased by TIE fighters.</i>

107
00:05:52.853 --> 00:05:56.273
Off it goes 'cause it's the fastest ship
in the galaxy.

108
00:05:56.356 --> 00:05:59.860
FOGLER: <i>When we started. I remember
being excited about building the Falcon.</i>

109
00:05:59.943 --> 00:06:02.821
and thinking.
"We'll look at the miniatures.

110
00:06:02.904 --> 00:06:05.824
"but we're going to make just the
most beautiful <i>Falcon</i> you've ever seen."

111
00:06:09.619 --> 00:06:13.832
<i>Going to actually look at the
five-foot Falcon that they built in 1976.</i>

112
00:06:13.915 --> 00:06:15.876
<i>and I walked away from that. thinking</i>

113
00:06:15.959 --> 00:06:19.588
<i>if we can make our digital version
look that good. we will be successful.</i>

114
00:06:19.671 --> 00:06:22.465
We really wanted to make it
as iconic as possible.

115
00:06:22.549 --> 00:06:28.972
<i>so we are trying to utilize more than
just rendering the CG elements.</i>

116
00:06:29.139 --> 00:06:31.057
On the original miniature of the Falcon.

117
00:06:31.141 --> 00:06:33.351
<i>the model makers
put on lots of little decals.</i>

118
00:06:33.435 --> 00:06:34.936
<i>and when we were doing research.</i>

119
00:06:35.020 --> 00:06:39.399
<i>we photographed all these tiny. tiny
little graphics that they put on</i>

120
00:06:39.482 --> 00:06:41.276
<i>and we put those on to our model.</i>

121
00:06:41.359 --> 00:06:45.572
<i>So. in lots of ways. our</i> Falcon
<i>really takes its cue</i>

122
00:06:45.655 --> 00:06:48.533
from the very original <i>Falcon</i> right down
to some of the smallest little details

123
00:06:48.617 --> 00:06:50.952
<i>that you'll never see on screen.
but we know they're there.</i>

124
00:06:53.914 --> 00:06:58.418
Any shot in The Force Awakens has
a great tapestry of different techniques

125
00:06:58.919 --> 00:07:03.340
<i>to an extent that you really can't tell
what's digital. what's real.</i>

126
00:07:03.423 --> 00:07:06.927
and they're all there for a reason.
they're all part of the story.

127
00:07:10.889 --> 00:07:14.476
ILM and Star Wars really
changed the way you saw

128
00:07:14.559 --> 00:07:16.478
<i>what was possible
in terms of visual effects.</i>

129
00:07:17.729 --> 00:07:23.276
<i>Bringing to life these worlds.
and these planets and these ships.</i>

130
00:07:23.360 --> 00:07:24.778
I can't say enough about ILM.

131
00:07:24.861 --> 00:07:27.072
<i>It's the most remarkable work
being done</i>

132
00:07:27.155 --> 00:07:31.076
<i>and I hope that audiences
appreciate what they're doing.</i>

133
00:07:31.910 --> 00:07:34.412
What makes it so challenging
and so exciting is

134
00:07:34.496 --> 00:07:36.164
so many people care about it.

135
00:07:36.581 --> 00:07:40.293
<i>but my goal. if you like.
is for people to just watch the movie</i>

136
00:07:40.377 --> 00:07:43.046
and imagine that these things
happened for real.

136
00:07:44.305 --> 00:08:44.832
